Minturnenses] the people of Minturnae, which was a city of Latium, on the via Appia, on the right bank of the Liris, on the borders of an extensive marsh, about three miles from the sea (Strab. v. p. 233). A colonia maritima with the rights of Roman citizens was established there in B.c. 296 (Liv. Χ 21, Vell. Pat. 1 14). In .B.C. 88 C. Marius, when flying from Rome by sea, was compelled to put in at the mouth of the Liris, and, endeavouring to conceal himself in the marshes, was dragged srom thence and imprisoned by order of the magistrates of Minturnae, who however afterwards released him and put him on board a ship which conveyed him to Africa.
